.TH RUFUSARM64-CLI 1 "16 July 2026" "RufusArm64 0.8.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
rufusarm64-cli \- safely create bootable USB media on Linux
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B rufusarm64-cli list
.RI [ --all ]
.RI [ --json ]
.PP
.B rufusarm64-cli inspect
.BI --image " FILE"
.RI [ --json ]
.PP
.B sudo rufusarm64-cli write
.BI --image " FILE"
.BI --device " /dev/DEVICE"
.RI [ options ]
.PP
.B sudo rufusarm64-cli verify
.BI --image " FILE"
.BI --device " /dev/DEVICE"
.PP
.B rufusarm64-cli hash
.I FILE
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B rufusarm64-cli
writes recognized GPT/MBR disk images and ISOHybrid Linux images directly, or
creates extracted Windows installation media. Windows media support GPT or MBR,
UEFI or x86-family BIOS/CSM, and Automatic, FAT32, or NTFS selection.
FAT32 media split oversized WIM/ESD files. NTFS/UEFI media add a pinned
UEFI:NTFS partition. BIOS/CSM media install an active MBR partition and
BOOTMGR-compatible MBR/PBR boot code. Compressed images are expanded privately before erasure; VHD, VHDX, QCOW2, and VMDK inputs are flattened with qemu-img.
.SH WRITE OPTIONS
.TP
.B --verify
Flush block buffers and compare copied data after writing. Recommended.
.TP
.BI --partition-scheme " gpt|mbr"
Choose the partition table for extracted Windows media. GPT is the default.
BIOS/CSM requires MBR.
.TP
.BI --target-system " uefi|bios"
Choose UEFI (non-CSM) or legacy BIOS/UEFI-CSM. BIOS is accepted only for MBR
media made from a compatible x86 or x86-64 Windows ISO containing root
.BR bootmgr .
Windows ARM64 is UEFI-only.
.TP
.BI --filesystem " auto|fat32|ntfs"
Choose the Windows-media filesystem. Automatic prefers FAT32 when every path and
file can be represented safely and otherwise selects NTFS. FAT32 splits an
oversized Windows installation image. NTFS/UEFI uses the bundled UEFI:NTFS
loader; NTFS/BIOS uses the Windows BOOTMGR partition boot record.
.TP
.BI --cluster-size " auto|4096|8192|16384|32768"
Choose the allocation-unit size for extracted Windows media.
.TP
.BI --dbx-file " FILE"
Parse a Microsoft DBXUpdate.bin or raw EFI signature database and reject Windows EFI boot files whose Authenticode hash or embedded X.509 certificate is revoked. This does not modify firmware.
.TP
.BI --driver-folder " DIRECTORY"
Validate a directory containing complete Windows driver packages and copy it to
.BR USB\\drivers .
The generated windowsPE answer file attempts to load each .inf package before
disk selection. The same folder remains available through Windows Setup's
.B Load driver
button. Drivers are not injected into boot.wim.
.TP
.B --full-format
Zero-write the complete new Windows data partition before formatting.
.TP
.B --bad-block-check
Zero-write and read back the complete new Windows data partition before formatting.
This is one destructive zero-pattern pass and can take a long time.
.TP
.B --yes
Skip the interactive destructive-operation confirmation.
.TP
.B --allow-fixed
Permit a non-removable whole disk after all other safety checks pass.
.TP
.B --allow-foreign-windows-architecture
Allow UEFI Windows media whose architecture does not match the ARM64 host. BIOS
media are architecture-gated separately and require x86-family Windows boot files.
.TP
.B --force-raw
Expert override that forces raw writing of a deliberately unrecognized or plain optical image.
.TP
.B --no-unmount
Do not issue initial unmount commands. The operation is still refused if a
filesystem is mounted at the final safety check.
.TP
.B --dry-run
Perform discovery, signature, size, source-identity, and target-safety checks without writing.
.TP
.BI --expected-identity " TOKEN"
Require the selected device to match a token returned by the JSON list command.
The graphical application always supplies this fail-closed check.
.SH SECURE BOOT DBX COMMANDS
.TP
.B dbx inspect (--file FILE | --firmware) [--json]
Parse and summarize an authenticated-update-format or firmware EFI DBX.
.TP
.B dbx update [--arch ARCH] [--output FILE] [--json]
Download the architecture-specific DBXUpdate.bin from Microsoft’s secureboot_objects repository and cache it with mode 0600.
.TP
.B dbx check (--dbx FILE | --firmware) --efi FILE [--json]
Calculate the PE/COFF Authenticode SHA-256 digest and inspect embedded PKCS#7 certificates. Exit non-zero when the image or an exact embedded certificate is revoked.
.TP
.B dbx scan (--dbx FILE | --firmware) --directory DIR [--json]
Scan bounded EFI boot files beneath a mounted directory.
.SH SIGNED IMAGE ACQUISITION COMMANDS
.TP
.B acquire verify --catalog FILE --signature FILE --public-key FILE [--json]
Verify the detached Ed25519 signature over the exact catalog bytes, reject expired or malformed metadata, and report the catalog digest and image count.
.TP
.B acquire list --catalog FILE --signature FILE --public-key FILE [--json]
List entries only after the complete signed catalog has passed strict schema, URL, filename, size, digest, redirect-host, and expiry validation.
.TP
.B acquire download --catalog FILE --signature FILE --public-key FILE --id ID [--output FILE|DIR] [--replace] [--json] [--json-progress]
Download one immutable catalog entry over HTTPS. Redirects are limited to hosts named by the signed catalog. The response must match the signed size and SHA-256. Data are written to a private temporary file, synchronized, and atomically installed only after verification. An existing file is reused only when its full size and hash match; a different regular file requires
.BR --replace .
Cancellation removes the temporary partial file.
.SH SAFETY
The program refuses partitions, read-only targets, the running root disk, and an
image stored on the selected target. It holds and hashes the selected source
through an open descriptor, refreshes target identity immediately before
destructive work, locks the target, verifies bundled boot assets, removes stale
signatures, flushes block buffers, and verifies copied files and filesystems.
.SH EXIT STATUS
Zero indicates success. A non-zero status indicates refusal, cancellation,
validation failure, I/O failure, filesystem failure, or verification mismatch.
